<subSubSection id="C30798E0FFF3A121D79146E5AADAFEA2" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="112" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA2CB6BFFF3A121D79146E5AADAFEA2" blockId="10.[151,1436,1817,2022]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1436,151,320]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="112" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFF3A120D79146E5A817F821" bold="true" box="[199,314,1925,1950]" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Externally, this golden irridescent moth resembles only the similarly colored Peruvian 
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFF3A120D26646E6A9DBF87D" authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFF3A120D26646E6ACB1F821" box="[1328,1436,1925,1950]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">S. andina</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
(see illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8CB69AFFF3A120D68E46C9AA3BF87D" author="Puplesis" box="[472,790,1961,1986]" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum (Entomology), 69 (1), 3 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">
Puplesis &amp; Robinson 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFF3A120D58C46CAAA3BF87D" box="[730,790,1962,1986]" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFF3A120D40146CAAAAEF87D" box="[855,899,1962,1986]" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" value="209.0">209</number>
) from which it differs in the distinctly broad abdominal apex and distally narrowing anterior apophyses in female genitalia; in contrast to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFF3A120D3EB46AEAC05F859" box="[1213,1320,1997,2022]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFF3A120D3EB46AEAC05F859" box="[1213,1320,1997,2022]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="111">S. andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, posterior apophyses are more or less straight (not outwardly bent as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFF2A121D40741F8AA91FF0F" box="[849,956,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFF2A121D40741F8AA91FF0F" box="[849,956,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">S. andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). From all newly described species in this paper, which are dark and with fascia, it clearly differs externally; also see female genitalia comparison provided in 
<figureCitation id="1326D7EEFFF2A121D7C141BFA835FF47" box="[151,280,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 54" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1888,1911]" captionTargetBox="[249,1406,208,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,193,1867]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 54. Female genitalia of Stigmella species feeding on Baccharis (ZMUC). 51, S. species 610; 52, S. latifoliae Remeikis, Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., not belonging to the type-series; 53, S. baccharicola Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., not belonging to the type-series; 54, S. species 609." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261797/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">
Figs 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFF2A121D79841BFA835FF47" box="[206,280,223,248]" pageId="11" pageNumber="112" value="52.5" valueMax="54.0" valueMin="51.0">51–54</number>
</figureCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFF2A121D67441BFA8A6FF47" box="[290,395,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFF2A121D67441BFA8A6FF47" box="[290,395,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFF2A121D6BC41BFAB39FF47" box="[490,532,223,248]" pageId="11" pageNumber="112" value="610.0">610</number>
is recognisable by the very large accessory sac and shape of the apophyses (
<figureCitation id="1326D7EEFFF2A121D23841BFA99BFEA2" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 54" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1888,1911]" captionTargetBox="[249,1406,208,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,193,1867]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 54. Female genitalia of Stigmella species feeding on Baccharis (ZMUC). 51, S. species 610; 52, S. latifoliae Remeikis, Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., not belonging to the type-series; 53, S. baccharicola Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., not belonging to the type-series; 54, S. species 609." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261797/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">
Fig. 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFF2A121D7C14064A99BFEA2" box="[151,182,260,285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="112" value="51.0">51</number>
</figureCitation>
); the host-plant, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFF2A121D6244064AB4EFEA2" box="[370,611,260,285]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="11" pageNumber="112" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusifolia">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFF2A121D6244064AB4EFEA2" box="[370,611,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="112">Baccharis obtusifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also makes this species distinctive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
